All this is just geometry.

00:02:51.740 --> 00:02:52.240
OK.

00:02:52.240 --> 00:02:55.980
So when you write
this down, you are

00:02:55.980 --> 00:03:00.060
agnostic about the form of a
and you have no information

00:03:00.060 --> 00:03:03.720
about the value of k.

00:03:03.720 --> 00:03:07.170
So to get more insight
into what's going on,

00:03:07.170 --> 00:03:08.800
you need to couple
this to your source.

00:03:08.800 --> 00:03:10.650
And so we take these things.

00:03:10.650 --> 00:03:12.660
And using the Einstein
field equations,

00:03:12.660 --> 00:03:18.540
you equate these to a perfect
fluid stress energy tensor.

00:03:18.540 --> 00:03:23.130
What pops out of that
are a pair of equations

00:03:23.130 --> 00:03:25.470
that arise in the
Einstein field equations.

00:03:25.470 --> 00:03:26.880
I call these F1 and F2.

00:03:26.880 --> 00:03:29.100
These are the two
Friedmann equations.

00:03:29.100 --> 00:03:32.455
F1 tells me about the velocity
associated with that expansion

00:03:32.455 --> 00:03:32.955
premise.

00:03:32.955 --> 00:03:35.490
There's an a dot
divided by a squared.

00:03:35.490 --> 00:03:38.550
We call that the Hubble
parameter, h of a squared.

00:03:38.550 --> 00:03:41.880
And it's related to the density
of the source of your universe

00:03:41.880 --> 00:03:43.580
as well as this kappa term.

00:03:43.580 --> 00:03:44.100
OK.

00:03:44.100 --> 00:03:48.660
And as we saw last time,
we can get some information

00:03:48.660 --> 00:03:51.670
about kappa from this equation.

00:03:51.670 --> 00:03:55.110
The second Friedmann equation
relates the acceleration

00:03:55.110 --> 00:03:57.300
of this expansion
term, a double dot--

00:03:57.300 --> 00:03:59.430
dot, by the way, d by dy.

00:03:59.430 --> 00:04:02.490
A double dot divided
by a is simply

00:04:02.490 --> 00:04:05.730
related to a quantity
that is the density plus 3

00:04:05.730 --> 00:04:08.430
times the pressure of this
perfect fluid that makes up

00:04:08.430 --> 00:04:10.110
our universe.

00:04:10.110 --> 00:04:14.220
We also find by requiring that
local energy conservation be

00:04:14.220 --> 00:04:16.470
held, in other words that
your stress energy tensor be

00:04:16.470 --> 00:04:19.500
divergence free, we
have a constraint that

00:04:19.500 --> 00:04:21.899
relates the amount of energy--

00:04:21.899 --> 00:04:24.450
the rate of change of energy
in a fiducial volume--

00:04:24.450 --> 00:04:28.200
to the negative pressure
times the rate of change

00:04:28.200 --> 00:04:29.910
of that fiducial volume.

00:04:29.910 --> 00:04:32.220
And this, as I discussed
in the last lecture,

00:04:32.220 --> 00:04:34.830
is essentially nothing
more than the first law

00:04:34.830 --> 00:04:36.030
of thermodynamics.

00:04:36.030 --> 00:04:37.920
It's written up
in fancy language

00:04:37.920 --> 00:04:41.055
appropriate to a
cosmological spacetime.

00:04:41.055 --> 00:04:42.930
As we move forward, we
find it useful to make

00:04:42.930 --> 00:04:45.090
a couple of definitions.

00:04:45.090 --> 00:04:48.480
So if you divide the
Hubble parameter squared

00:04:48.480 --> 00:04:50.160
by Newton's
gravitational constant,

00:04:50.160 --> 00:04:53.320
that's got the
dimensions of density.

00:04:53.320 --> 00:04:56.030
And so we're going to define
a critical density to be 3h

00:04:56.030 --> 00:04:57.840
squared over 8 pi g.

00:04:57.840 --> 00:05:02.850
And we're going to define
density parameters, omega,

00:05:02.850 --> 00:05:05.350
as the actual physical
density is normalized

00:05:05.350 --> 00:05:06.900
to that critical density.

00:05:06.900 --> 00:05:10.530
And when you do this, you
find that the critical--

00:05:10.530 --> 00:05:13.700
the first Friedmann equation
can be written as omega--

00:05:13.700 --> 00:05:15.470
oh, that's a typo--

