that most cosmologists use,

00:08:07.060 --> 00:08:08.800
each species will
have a pressure

00:08:08.800 --> 00:08:10.590
that is linear in the density.

00:08:21.220 --> 00:08:25.950
If you do choose
that form, then when

00:08:25.950 --> 00:08:31.590
you enforce local conservation
of energy, what you will then

00:08:31.590 --> 00:08:45.860
find is that for every
one of your species,

00:08:45.860 --> 00:08:50.567
there is a simple relationship.

00:08:50.567 --> 00:08:52.150
There's a simple
differential equation

00:08:52.150 --> 00:08:54.280
that governs how
that species evolves

00:08:54.280 --> 00:08:56.680
as the scale factor changes.

00:08:56.680 --> 00:09:02.920
This can be immediately
integrated up

00:09:02.920 --> 00:09:06.010
to find that the amount of,
at some particular moment,

00:09:06.010 --> 00:09:09.400
the density of species i
depends on how it looks.

00:09:09.400 --> 00:09:12.440
So 0 again denotes now.

00:09:12.440 --> 00:09:16.930
It is simply proportional to
some power of the scale factor

00:09:16.930 --> 00:09:27.270
where the power that enters
here can be simply calculated

00:09:27.270 --> 00:09:29.740
given that equation
of state parameter.

00:09:29.740 --> 00:09:38.210
Once you have these things
together, you're ready to roll.

00:09:38.210 --> 00:09:39.710
You've got your
Friedmann equations.

00:09:39.710 --> 00:09:42.230
You've got all the
