00:26:11.560 --> 00:26:16.930
When it propagates to us, we
define our scale factor as 1,

00:26:16.930 --> 00:26:21.402
the energy will have fallen
down by a factor of 1 over a.

00:26:21.402 --> 00:26:23.860
So this makes it a little bit
more rigorous, this intuitive

00:26:23.860 --> 00:26:26.200
argument that we
saw from considering

00:26:26.200 --> 00:26:28.450
how the density of
radiation fell off.

00:26:28.450 --> 00:26:33.160
What we see is the energy
is indeed redshifting

00:26:33.160 --> 00:26:35.810
with the scale factor.

00:26:35.810 --> 00:26:41.350
So if I use the fact that
the energy that I observe--

00:26:45.150 --> 00:26:48.470
if I'm measuring light, light
has a frequency of omega--

00:26:51.470 --> 00:26:57.050
what I see is the omega
that I observe at my scale

00:26:57.050 --> 00:27:00.770
factor, which I define to
be 1, normalized to that

00:27:00.770 --> 00:27:09.660
when it was emitted, it
looks like the scale factor

00:27:09.660 --> 00:27:12.240
when it was admitted.

00:27:12.240 --> 00:27:16.740
Divided by a now, a observed.

00:27:16.740 --> 00:27:17.490
I call this 1.

00:27:23.700 --> 00:27:25.180
I can flip this
over, another way

00:27:25.180 --> 00:27:28.920
of saying this is
that, if I write it

00:27:28.920 --> 00:27:37.240
in terms of wavelengths of
the radiation, the wavelength

00:27:37.240 --> 00:27:41.710
of the radiation and when it was
emitted versus the wavelength

00:27:41.710 --> 00:27:45.850
that we observe it tells
me about the scale factor

00:27:45.850 --> 00:27:48.550
when the radiation was emitted.

00:28:02.010 --> 00:28:04.215
Astronomers like to
work with redshift.

00:28:06.780 --> 00:28:08.310
They like to work
with wavelength

00:28:08.310 --> 00:28:12.450
when they study things
like the spectra

00:28:12.450 --> 00:28:13.920
of distant astronomical objects.

00:28:17.890 --> 00:28:22.600
And they use it to define
a notion of redshift.

00:28:22.600 --> 00:28:27.730
So we define the redshift
z to be the wavelength

00:28:27.730 --> 00:28:32.020
that we observe, minus the
wavelength at the radiation

00:28:32.020 --> 00:28:36.010
that when it is emitted
divided by the wavelength when

00:28:36.010 --> 00:28:38.170
it was emitted.

00:28:38.170 --> 00:28:41.650
Put all of these
definitions together,

00:28:41.650 --> 00:28:43.990
and what this tells
me is that the scale

00:28:43.990 --> 00:28:50.340
factor at which the
radiation was emitted

00:28:50.340 --> 00:28:55.630
is simply related to the
redshift that we observe.

00:28:55.630 --> 00:29:00.690
So this at last gives us
a direct and not terribly

00:29:00.690 --> 00:29:02.910
difficult to use
observational proxy

00:29:02.910 --> 00:29:06.960
that directly encodes the
scale factor of our universe.

00:29:06.960 --> 00:29:23.060
Suppose we measure the spectrum
of radiation from some source,

00:29:23.060 --> 00:29:27.710
and we see the
distinct fingerprint

00:29:27.710 --> 00:29:30.740
associated with emission
from a particular set

00:29:30.740 --> 00:29:32.399
of atomic transitions.

00:29:38.390 --> 00:29:45.370
What we generally find is
some well-known fingerprints

00:29:45.370 --> 00:29:58.040
of well-characterized
transitions,

00:29:58.040 --> 00:30:17.938
but in general they are
stretched by some factor

00:30:17.938 --> 00:30:20.180
that we call the redshift z.

00:30:20.180 --> 00:30:22.680
Actually, you usually stretch
by-- when you go through this,

00:30:22.680 --> 00:30:23.720
you'll find that
what you measure

00:30:23.720 --> 00:30:25.300
is actually stretched
by 1 plus z.

00:30:30.840 --> 00:30:32.430
You measure that,
you have measured

00:30:32.430 --> 00:30:35.170
the scale factor at which
this radiation was measured--

00:30:35.170 --> 00:30:35.670
was emitted.

00:30:51.300 --> 00:30:52.360
So this is beautiful.

00:30:52.360 --> 00:30:54.450
This is a way in which
the universe hands

00:30:54.450 --> 00:31:02.010
us the tool by which we can
directly characterize some

00:31:02.010 --> 00:31:04.200
of the geometry of the
universe at which light

00:31:04.200 --> 00:31:05.772
has been emitted.

00:31:05.772 --> 00:31:07.230
This is actually
one of the reasons

00:31:07.230 --> 00:31:13.770
why a lot of people who do
observational cosmology also

00:31:13.770 --> 00:31:16.470
happen to be expert
atomic spectroscopists.

00:31:16.470 --> 00:31:19.260
Because you want to know
to very high precision what

00:31:19.260 --> 00:31:22.127
is the characteristics of
the hydrogen Balmer lines.

00:31:22.127 --> 00:31:24.210
Some of the most important
sources for doing these

00:31:24.210 --> 00:31:26.520
tend to be galaxies
in which there's

00:31:26.520 --> 00:31:29.520
a lot of matter falling onto
black holes, some of the topics

00:31:29.520 --> 00:31:32.520
we'll be talking about
in an upcoming video.

00:31:32.520 --> 00:31:34.830
As that material
falls in, it gets hot,

00:31:34.830 --> 00:31:36.780
it generates a lot of
radiation, and you'll

00:31:36.780 --> 00:31:39.990
see things like transition
lines associated

00:31:39.990 --> 00:31:42.180
with carbon and iron.

00:31:42.180 --> 00:31:45.455
But often all reddened
by a factor of several.

00:31:45.455 --> 00:31:46.830
You sort of go,
oh, look at that,

00:31:46.830 --> 00:31:51.450
carbon falling onto a
black hole at redshift 4.8.

00:31:51.450 --> 00:31:53.280
That is happening at
a time when the scale

00:31:53.280 --> 00:31:57.990
factor of the universe
was 1 over 4.8--

00:31:57.990 --> 00:32:00.560
or 1 over 5.8, forgot my
factor of 1 plus there.

00:32:03.890 --> 00:32:08.870
So you measure the
redshift, and you

00:32:08.870 --> 00:32:10.240
have measured the scale factor.

00:32:15.040 --> 00:32:17.710
But you don't know when
that light was emitted.

00:32:21.730 --> 00:32:24.400
We need to connect
the scale factor

00:32:24.400 --> 00:32:30.970
that we can measure so
directly and so beautifully

00:32:30.970 --> 00:32:34.870
to the time at which
it was emitted.

00:32:34.870 --> 00:32:37.490
We now have a way
of determining a,

00:32:37.490 --> 00:32:39.640
but we need a as
a function of t.

00:33:07.950 --> 00:33:11.100
And in truth, we do this
kind of via a surrogate.

00:33:11.100 --> 00:33:15.240
Because we are using
radiation as our tool

00:33:15.240 --> 00:33:18.000
for probing the scale
factor, we really

00:33:18.000 --> 00:33:20.430
don't measure t directly.

00:33:20.430 --> 00:33:22.650
When we look at light
and it's coming to us,

00:33:22.650 --> 00:33:26.190
it doesn't say I
was emitted on March

00:33:26.190 --> 00:33:31.590
27th of the year
negative 6.8 billion

00:33:31.590 --> 00:33:34.380
BC, or something like that.

00:33:34.380 --> 00:33:37.140
We do know, though,
that it traveled

00:33:37.140 --> 00:33:39.970
towards us at the speed of
light on a null geodesic.

00:33:39.970 --> 00:33:42.120
And because it's
a null geodesic,

00:33:42.120 --> 00:33:43.730
there's a very simple--

00:33:43.730 --> 00:33:45.480
simple's a little bit
of an overstatement,

00:33:45.480 --> 00:33:49.800
but there is at least a
calculable connection.

00:33:49.800 --> 00:33:52.755
Because it's moving at the
speed of light, we can simply--

00:33:52.755 --> 00:33:54.150
I should stop using that word--

00:33:54.150 --> 00:33:58.440
we can connect time to space.

00:33:58.440 --> 00:34:00.360
And so rather than
directly determining

00:34:00.360 --> 00:34:02.940
the time at which the
radiation was emitted,

00:34:02.940 --> 00:34:07.463
we want to calculate the
distance of the source from us

00:34:07.463 --> 00:34:08.130
that emitted it.

00:34:41.170 --> 00:34:44.580
So rather than directly
building up a of t,

00:34:44.580 --> 00:34:47.520
we're going to build
up an a of d, where d

00:34:47.520 --> 00:34:50.540
is the distance of the source.

00:34:50.540 --> 00:34:52.739
And if you're used to working
in Euclidean geometry,

00:34:52.739 --> 00:34:54.540
you sort of go, ah, OK, great.

00:34:54.540 --> 00:34:57.570
I know that light travels
at the speed of light,

00:34:57.570 --> 00:35:00.180
so all I need to do is
divide the distance by c,

00:35:00.180 --> 00:35:03.900
and I've got the time,
and I build a of t.

00:35:03.900 --> 00:35:05.513
Conceptually, that
is roughly right,

00:35:05.513 --> 00:35:07.680
and that gives at least a
cartoon of the idea that's

00:35:07.680 --> 00:35:08.800
going on here.

00:35:08.800 --> 00:35:11.890
But we have to be a
little bit careful.

00:35:11.890 --> 00:35:15.330
Because it turns out when
you are making measurements

00:35:15.330 --> 00:35:21.900
in a curved space time, the
notion of distance that you use

00:35:21.900 --> 00:35:26.650
depends on how you make
the distance measurement.

00:35:26.650 --> 00:35:30.780
So this leads us now to our
discussion of distance measures

00:35:30.780 --> 00:35:32.661
in cosmological spacetime.

00:35:55.262 --> 00:35:56.970
So just to give a
little bit of intuition

00:35:56.970 --> 00:35:59.280
as to what's the
kind of calculation

00:35:59.280 --> 00:36:01.890
we're going to need to do,
let me describe one distance

00:36:01.890 --> 00:36:06.240
measure that is observation,
which is about useless,

00:36:06.240 --> 00:36:09.390
but not a bad thing
to at least begin

00:36:09.390 --> 00:36:15.540
to get a handle on, the
way different parameters

00:36:15.540 --> 00:36:17.400
of the spacetime
come in and influence

00:36:17.400 --> 00:36:19.450
what the distance measure is.

00:36:19.450 --> 00:36:22.800
