Notice that whatever is going
on your scale factor, your a,

00:39:49.350 --> 00:39:51.380
your distance is
going to track that.

00:39:51.380 --> 00:39:53.818
As a consequence of
this, two objects

00:39:53.818 --> 00:39:55.610
that are sitting in
what we call the Hubble

00:39:55.610 --> 00:39:57.290
flow, in other words,
two objects that

00:39:57.290 --> 00:40:00.560
are co-moving with the
fluid that makes up

00:40:00.560 --> 00:40:03.150
the source of our universe.

00:40:03.150 --> 00:40:05.590
They have an apparent motion
with respect to each other.

00:40:19.420 --> 00:40:33.900
If I take the time
derivative of this,

00:40:33.900 --> 00:40:40.290
the apparent is just
a dot, or 0 chi,

00:40:40.290 --> 00:40:48.860
which is equal to the
Hubble parameter times dp.

00:40:48.860 --> 00:40:53.205
Recall that the Hubble
parameter is a dot over a,

00:40:53.205 --> 00:40:54.830
and if I'm doing this
right now, that's

00:40:54.830 --> 00:40:59.680
the value of the
Hubble parameter now.

00:40:59.680 --> 00:41:02.230
So this is the Hubble Expansion
Law, the very famous Hubble

00:41:02.230 --> 00:41:03.880
Expansion Law.

00:41:03.880 --> 00:41:05.613
So we can see it
hidden in this--

00:41:05.613 --> 00:41:07.030
not even really
hidden, it's quite

00:41:07.030 --> 00:41:09.550
apparent in this notion of
an instantaneous physical

00:41:09.550 --> 00:41:10.690
distance.

00:41:10.690 --> 00:41:12.620
Let me just finally
emphasize, though,

00:41:12.620 --> 00:41:15.070
that the instantanaeity
that is part

00:41:15.070 --> 00:41:25.860
of this object's name,
instantaneous measurements,

00:41:25.860 --> 00:41:27.210
are not done.

00:41:29.895 --> 00:41:31.630
As I said-- I mean,
this is it sounds

00:41:31.630 --> 00:41:33.630
like I'm being slightly
facetious, but it's not.

00:41:33.630 --> 00:41:36.195
The meaning of this
distance measure

00:41:36.195 --> 00:41:37.820
is, like I said, it's
a yardstick where

00:41:37.820 --> 00:41:41.070
I have an event at me, the
other end of my yardstick

00:41:41.070 --> 00:41:44.210
is at my cosmological event.

00:41:44.210 --> 00:41:46.900
Those are typically
separated by millions,

00:41:46.900 --> 00:41:49.410
billions of light years.

00:41:49.410 --> 00:41:50.490
Even if you could--

00:41:50.490 --> 00:41:52.740
OK, the facetious bit was
imagining it as a yardstick.

00:41:52.740 --> 00:41:54.630
But the non-facetious
point I want to make

00:41:54.630 --> 00:41:57.360
is we do not make instantaneous
measurements with that.

00:41:57.360 --> 00:42:00.420
When I measure an event that is
billions of light years away,

00:42:00.420 --> 00:42:02.790
I am of course
measuring it using light

00:42:02.790 --> 00:42:07.240
and I'm seeing light that was
emitted billions of years ago.

00:42:07.240 --> 00:42:08.880
So we need to think
a little bit more

00:42:08.880 --> 00:42:19.310
carefully about how
to define distance

00:42:19.310 --> 00:42:22.220
in terms of quantities
that really correspond

00:42:22.220 --> 00:42:23.930
to measurements we can make.

00:42:43.630 --> 00:42:49.120
And to get a little
intuition, here

00:42:49.120 --> 00:42:57.400
are three ways where, if you
were living in Euclidean space

00:42:57.400 --> 00:43:07.540
and you were looking at
light from distant objects,

00:43:07.540 --> 00:43:09.730
here are three ways that
you could define distance.

00:43:18.160 --> 00:43:23.560
So if spacetime were that
of special relativity--

00:43:23.560 --> 00:43:25.800
well, let's just say if
space were purely Euclidean.

00:43:25.800 --> 00:43:27.050
Let's just leave it like that.

00:43:45.350 --> 00:43:47.930
Here are three notions
that we could use.

00:43:47.930 --> 00:43:53.390
One, imagine there was
some source of radiation

00:43:53.390 --> 00:43:57.620
in the universe that you
understood so well that you

00:43:57.620 --> 00:44:02.950
knew its intrinsic luminosity.

00:44:02.950 --> 00:44:14.100
What you could do is compare
the intrinsic luminosity

00:44:14.100 --> 00:44:16.419
of a source to its
apparent brightness.

00:44:30.120 --> 00:44:34.125
So let's let f be the flux
we measure from the source.

00:44:41.790 --> 00:44:46.970
This will be related to
l, the luminosity, which--

00:44:50.300 --> 00:44:51.846
suspend disbelief
for a moment, we

00:44:51.846 --> 00:44:55.090
want to imagine that we
know it for some reason.

00:44:55.090 --> 00:44:59.000
And if we imagine this
is an isotropic emitter,

00:44:59.000 --> 00:45:03.110
this will be related
by a factor of 4 pi,

00:45:03.110 --> 00:45:06.440
and the distance between
us and that source.

00:45:06.440 --> 00:45:09.020
Let's call this d sub l.

00:45:09.020 --> 00:45:12.035
This is a luminosity distance.

00:45:18.480 --> 00:45:22.140
It is a distance that
we measure by inferring

00:45:22.140 --> 00:45:25.350
the behavior of luminosity
of a distant object.

00:45:28.710 --> 00:45:31.330
Now it turns out, and this is a
subject for a different class,

00:45:31.330 --> 00:45:33.540
but nature actually
gives us some objects

00:45:33.540 --> 00:45:38.820
whose luminosity is known or
at least can be calibrated.

00:45:38.820 --> 00:45:43.590
In the case of much of what
is done in cosmology today,

00:45:43.590 --> 00:45:47.430
we can take advantage of the
behavior of certain stars

00:45:47.430 --> 00:45:52.520
whose luminosity is strongly
correlated to the way that--

00:45:52.520 --> 00:45:54.870
these are stars whose
luminosity is variable,

00:45:54.870 --> 00:45:57.585
and we can use the fact that
their variability is correlated

00:45:57.585 --> 00:46:02.310
to their luminosity to infer
what their absolute luminosity

00:46:02.310 --> 00:46:03.720
actually is.

00:46:03.720 --> 00:46:06.690
There are other supernova
events whose luminosity

00:46:06.690 --> 00:46:09.830
likewise appears to
follow a universal law.

00:46:09.830 --> 00:46:14.310
It's related to the
fact that the properties

00:46:14.310 --> 00:46:16.740
of those explosions are
actually set by the microphysics

00:46:16.740 --> 00:46:18.750
of the stars that set them.

00:46:18.750 --> 00:46:22.920
More recently, we've been
able to exploit the fact

00:46:22.920 --> 00:46:27.570
that gravitational wave sources
have an intrinsic luminosity

00:46:27.570 --> 00:46:29.953
in gravitational waves,
the dedt associated

00:46:29.953 --> 00:46:32.220
with the gravitational
waves that they emit,

00:46:32.220 --> 00:46:35.400
which depends on the source
gravitational physics in a very

00:46:35.400 --> 00:46:37.650
simple and predictable
way that doesn't

00:46:37.650 --> 00:46:39.522
depend on very many parameters.

00:46:39.522 --> 00:46:40.980
I actually did a
little bit of work

00:46:40.980 --> 00:46:43.830
on that over the
course of my career,

00:46:43.830 --> 00:46:46.170
and it's a very
exciting development

00:46:46.170 --> 00:46:48.300
that we can now use
these as a way of setting

00:46:48.300 --> 00:46:51.170
the intrinsic luminosity
of certain sources.

00:46:51.170 --> 00:46:54.630
At any rate, if you can take
advantage of these objects that

00:46:54.630 --> 00:46:56.880
have a known luminosity
and you can then

00:46:56.880 --> 00:46:59.160
measure the flux of
radiation in your detector

00:46:59.160 --> 00:47:02.910
from these things, you
have learned the distance.

00:47:02.910 --> 00:47:05.483
At least you have learned
this particular measure

00:47:05.483 --> 00:47:06.150
of the distance.

00:47:13.348 --> 00:47:14.140
That's measure one.

00:47:26.990 --> 00:47:32.270
Measure two is imagine
you have some object

00:47:32.270 --> 00:47:37.100
in the sky that has a particular
intrinsic size associated

00:47:37.100 --> 00:47:38.955
with it.

00:47:38.955 --> 00:47:41.330
You can sort of think of the
objects whose luminosity you

00:47:41.330 --> 00:47:43.910
know about as standard candles.

00:47:43.910 --> 00:47:46.550
Imagine if nature builds
standard yardsticks,

00:47:46.550 --> 00:47:49.220
there's some object whose
size you always know.

00:47:52.670 --> 00:47:59.750
Well, let's compare that
physical size to the angular

00:47:59.750 --> 00:48:00.800
size that you measure.

00:48:08.240 --> 00:48:21.680
The angle that the object
sub tends in the sky

00:48:21.680 --> 00:48:31.410
is going to be that intrinsic
size, delta l divided

00:48:31.410 --> 00:48:33.190
by the distance.

00:48:33.190 --> 00:48:37.720
We'll call this distance d sub
a, for the angular diameter

00:48:37.720 --> 00:48:38.220
distance.

00:48:57.032 --> 00:48:58.490
Believe it or not,
nature, in fact,

00:48:58.490 --> 00:49:00.860
provides standard
yardsticks type

00:49:00.860 --> 00:49:02.360
so that we can actually do this.

00:49:05.070 --> 00:49:06.900
Finally, at least as
a matter of principle,

00:49:06.900 --> 00:49:08.370
imagine you had
some object that's

00:49:08.370 --> 00:49:11.670
moving across the sky with
a speed that you know.

00:49:11.670 --> 00:49:22.150
You could compare
that transverse speed

00:49:22.150 --> 00:49:24.700
to an apparent angular speed.

00:49:37.610 --> 00:49:39.490
So the theta dot,
the angular speed

00:49:39.490 --> 00:50:02.130
that you measure, that
would be the velocity

00:50:02.130 --> 00:50:10.520
perpendicular to your line
of sight divided by distance.

00:50:10.520 --> 00:50:17.720
We'll call this d sub m,
the proper motion distance.

00:50:30.720 --> 00:50:32.330
So if our universe
were Euclidean,

00:50:32.330 --> 00:50:34.635
not only would it be easy
for us to use these three

00:50:34.635 --> 00:50:36.260
measures of distance,
all three of them

00:50:36.260 --> 00:50:41.807
would give the same
result. Because this is all

00:50:41.807 --> 00:50:42.390
just geometry.

00:50:50.370 --> 00:50:54.370
Turns out when you study
these notions of distance,

00:50:54.370 --> 00:51:00.250
in an FRW spacetime, there's
some variation that enters.

00:51:00.250 --> 00:51:06.740
Let me just emphasize here that
there is an excellent summary

00:51:06.740 --> 00:51:07.590
on this stuff.

00:51:07.590 --> 00:51:09.320
I can't remember if I linked
this to the course website

00:51:09.320 --> 00:51:09.820
or not.

00:51:09.820 --> 00:51:10.820
I should and I shall.

00:51:14.300 --> 00:51:16.910
An excellent
summary of all this,

00:51:16.910 --> 00:51:22.010
really emphasizing
observationally significant

00:51:22.010 --> 00:51:26.240
aspects of these things
come from the article that

00:51:26.240 --> 00:51:43.620
is on the archive called
Distance Measures in Cosmology

00:51:43.620 --> 00:51:49.996
by David Hogg, a colleague
at New York University.

00:51:55.460 --> 00:52:02.660
You can find this on the
Astro PH archive, 9905116.

00:52:02.660 --> 00:52:06.010
It's hard for me to believe
this is almost 21 years old now.

00:52:06.010 --> 00:52:07.835
This is a gem of a paper.

00:52:07.835 --> 00:52:09.460
Hogg never submitted
it to any journal,

00:52:09.460 --> 00:52:11.250
just posted it on the
archive so that the community

00:52:11.250 --> 00:52:12.375
could take advantage of it.

00:52:16.700 --> 00:52:21.370
So the textbook by Carroll goes
through the calculation of d

00:52:21.370 --> 00:52:24.270
sub l.

00:52:24.270 --> 00:52:27.480
On a problem set
you will do d sub m.

00:52:27.480 --> 00:52:29.490
We're going to go
through d sub a,

00:52:29.490 --> 00:52:32.490
just so you can see some
of the way that this works.

00:52:32.490 --> 00:52:42.890
Let me emphasize one thing,
all of these measures

00:52:42.890 --> 00:52:44.440
use the first
Friedmann equation.

00:52:57.860 --> 00:53:00.830
So writing your Friedmann
equation like so.

00:53:00.830 --> 00:53:03.830
i is a sum of all
the different species

00:53:03.830 --> 00:53:07.010
of things that can contribute
including curvature.

00:53:07.010 --> 00:53:09.500
So recall that even though
curvature isn't really

00:53:09.500 --> 00:53:13.010
a density, you can
combine enough factors

00:53:13.010 --> 00:53:15.170
to make it act as though
it were a density.

00:53:19.600 --> 00:53:21.692
You assume a power law.

00:53:31.340 --> 00:53:34.390
So this n sub i is related to
the equation of state parameter

00:53:34.390 --> 00:53:36.023
for each one of these species.

00:53:36.023 --> 00:53:37.690
And let's now take
advantage of the fact

00:53:37.690 --> 00:53:42.070
that we know the scale factor
directly ties to redshift.

00:53:42.070 --> 00:53:44.500
I can rewrite this as
how the density evolves

00:53:44.500 --> 00:53:46.960
as a function of redshift.

00:53:46.960 --> 00:53:49.540
So when you put all
of this together,

00:53:49.540 --> 00:53:56.635
this allows us to
write h of a as h of z.

00:54:02.260 --> 00:54:04.840
This is given by the
Hubble parameter now

00:54:04.840 --> 00:54:06.650
times some function e of z.

00:54:23.280 --> 00:54:24.650
And that is simply--

00:54:24.650 --> 00:54:26.680
you divide everything
out to normalize

00:54:26.680 --> 00:54:28.660
to the critical
density, and that

00:54:28.660 --> 00:54:34.410
is a sum over all these
densities with the redshift

00:54:34.410 --> 00:54:35.160
waiting like so.

00:54:42.120 --> 00:54:43.810
Let's really do an
example, like I said.

00:54:43.810 --> 00:54:48.190
So if you read Carroll, you
will see the calculation

00:54:48.190 --> 00:54:49.840
of the luminosity distance.

00:54:49.840 --> 00:54:53.585
If you do the cosmology
problem set that will be--

00:54:53.585 --> 00:54:59.420
I believe its p set 8, you
will explore the proper motion

00:54:59.420 --> 00:54:59.920
distance.

00:55:02.580 --> 00:55:05.950
So let's do the angular
diameter distance.

00:55:05.950 --> 00:55:07.700
Seeing someone work
through this, I think,

00:55:07.700 --> 00:55:10.070
is probably useful for
helping to solidify

00:55:10.070 --> 00:55:12.530
the way in which these
distance measures work

00:55:12.530 --> 00:55:20.430
and how it is that one can tie
together important observables.

00:55:20.430 --> 00:55:24.740
So let's consider
some source that we

00:55:24.740 --> 00:55:31.400
observe that, according to us,
subtends an angle, delta phi.

00:55:47.110 --> 00:55:50.670
Every spacial sector is
spherically symmetric,

00:55:50.670 --> 00:55:53.140
and so we can orient
our coordinate system

00:55:53.140 --> 00:55:56.080
so that this thing, it would
be sort of a standard ruler--

00:55:56.080 --> 00:55:58.690
what we're going to do is
orient our coordinate system

00:55:58.690 --> 00:56:02.940
so that object lies in the
theta equals pi over 2 plane.

00:56:23.820 --> 00:56:26.610
The proper size of that source--

00:56:26.610 --> 00:56:28.793
so the thing is just
sitting in the sky there--

00:56:28.793 --> 00:56:30.210
the proper size
of the source, you

00:56:30.210 --> 00:56:31.585
can get this in
the line element.

00:56:39.250 --> 00:56:42.140
The delta l of
the source will be

00:56:42.140 --> 00:56:46.820
the scale factor at the time
at which it is emitted, r0.

00:56:56.350 --> 00:57:00.310
So this is using one of the
forms of the FRW line elements

00:57:00.310 --> 00:57:04.050
I wrote down at the
beginning of this lecture.

00:57:04.050 --> 00:57:08.924
And so the angular
diameter distance,

00:57:08.924 --> 00:57:11.780
that's a quantity that
I've defined over here,

00:57:11.780 --> 00:57:17.910
it's just the ratio of
this length to that angle.

00:57:31.617 --> 00:57:33.200
Let's rewrite this
using the redshift.

00:57:33.200 --> 00:57:47.075
Redshift is something that
I actually directly observe,

00:57:47.075 --> 00:57:47.700
so there we go.

00:57:52.190 --> 00:57:57.350
This is not wrong,
but it's flawed.

00:57:57.350 --> 00:57:58.220
So this is true.

00:57:58.220 --> 00:57:59.250
This is absolutely true.

00:57:59.250 --> 00:58:02.360
Here's the problem, I don't
know the overall scale

00:58:02.360 --> 00:58:08.570
of my universe and this
coordinate chi doesn't really

00:58:08.570 --> 00:58:10.580
have an observable
meaning to it.

00:58:10.580 --> 00:58:14.300
It's how I label events, but I
look at some quasar in the sky

00:58:14.300 --> 00:58:17.540
and I'm like, what's your chi?

00:58:17.540 --> 00:58:23.660
So what we need to do is
reformulate the numerator

00:58:23.660 --> 00:58:27.050
of this expression in such a
way as to get rid of that chi

00:58:27.050 --> 00:58:29.180
and then see what happens,
see if we have a way

00:58:29.180 --> 00:58:30.458
to get rid of that r0.

00:58:30.458 --> 00:58:31.625
Let's worry about chi first.

00:58:39.210 --> 00:58:42.720
We're going to eliminate it by
taking advantage of the fact

00:58:42.720 --> 00:58:45.480
that the radiation
I am measuring

00:58:45.480 --> 00:58:46.995
comes to me on a null path.

00:59:01.150 --> 00:59:02.150
Not just any null path.

00:59:02.150 --> 00:59:04.210
I'm going imagine
it's a radial one.

00:59:04.210 --> 00:59:08.170
We are allowed to be somewhat
self-centered in defining

00:59:08.170 --> 00:59:10.810
FRW cosmology, we put
ourselves at the origin.

00:59:10.810 --> 00:59:13.510
So any light that
reaches us moves

00:59:13.510 --> 00:59:16.480
on a purely radial trajectory
from its source to us.

00:59:22.780 --> 00:59:32.380
So looking at how the time
and the radial coordinate chi

00:59:32.380 --> 00:59:40.105
are related for a radial null
path we go into our FRW metric.

00:59:51.530 --> 00:59:54.500
I get this.

00:59:54.500 --> 00:59:58.490
So I can integrate this up
to figure out what chi is.

01:00:13.090 --> 01:00:13.805
So this is right.

01:00:13.805 --> 01:00:15.430
Let's massage it a
little bit to put it

01:00:15.430 --> 01:00:17.710
in a form that's a little
bit more useful to us.

01:00:17.710 --> 01:00:19.870
Let's change our variable--

01:00:19.870 --> 01:00:22.390
change our variable of
integration from time to a.

01:00:27.010 --> 01:00:31.810
So this will be an integral
from the scale factor at which

01:00:31.810 --> 01:00:36.040
the radiation is emitted
to the scale factor

01:00:36.040 --> 01:00:38.180
which we observe it, i.e. now.

01:00:38.180 --> 01:00:43.420
And when you do that
change of variables

01:00:43.420 --> 01:00:46.590
your integral changes like so.

01:00:46.590 --> 01:00:53.513
Let's rewrite this once more
to insert my Hubble parameter.

01:01:29.995 --> 01:01:32.140
Now let's change
variables once more.

01:01:32.140 --> 01:01:35.080
We're going to use the fact
that our direct measurable is

01:01:35.080 --> 01:01:36.460
redshift.

01:01:36.460 --> 01:01:45.532
And so if we use a
equals 1 over 1 plus z,

01:01:45.532 --> 01:02:01.636
I can further write this as an
integral over redshift like so.

01:02:01.636 --> 01:02:03.630
And that h0 can come
out of my integral.

01:02:12.070 --> 01:02:15.360
So this is in a form that
is now finally formulated

01:02:15.360 --> 01:02:19.740
in terms of an
observable redshift

01:02:19.740 --> 01:02:22.470
and my model
dependent parameters.

01:02:22.470 --> 01:02:26.460
The various omegas that, when
I construct my universe model,

01:02:26.460 --> 01:02:27.570
I am free to set.

01:02:27.570 --> 01:02:30.035
Or if I am a
phenomenologist, that

01:02:30.035 --> 01:02:31.410
are going to be
knobs that I turn

01:02:31.410 --> 01:02:34.860
to try to design a model
universe that matches

01:02:34.860 --> 01:02:38.760
the data that I am measuring.

01:02:38.760 --> 01:02:41.800
r0, though, is still
kind of annoying.

01:02:41.800 --> 01:02:44.820
We don't know what
this guy is, so what

01:02:44.820 --> 01:03:00.490
we do is eliminate r0 in
favor of a curvature density

01:03:00.490 --> 01:03:01.336
parameter.

01:03:07.660 --> 01:03:10.590
So using the fact
that omega curvature--

01:03:15.400 --> 01:03:17.950
go back to how this was
originally defined--

01:03:17.950 --> 01:03:22.570
it was negative kappa
over h0 squared.

01:03:22.570 --> 01:03:26.590
That's negative k over
r0 squared h0 squared.

01:03:30.700 --> 01:03:39.650
That tells me that r0 is
the Hubble constant now,

01:03:39.650 --> 01:03:44.660
divided by the square
root of the absolute value

01:03:44.660 --> 01:03:50.550
of the curvature, at least
if k equals plus or minus 1.

01:03:50.550 --> 01:03:53.460
What happens when it's not plus
or minus 1, if it's equal to 0?

01:03:53.460 --> 01:03:54.460
Well, hold that thought.

01:04:11.720 --> 01:04:13.400
So let's put all
these pieces together.

01:04:35.720 --> 01:04:37.220
So assembling all
the ingredients

01:04:37.220 --> 01:04:43.180
I have here, what we find is
the angular diameter distance.

01:04:43.180 --> 01:04:47.570
There's a factor
of 1 over 1 plus z,

01:04:47.570 --> 01:04:49.280
1 over the Hubble constant.

01:04:49.280 --> 01:04:53.670
Remember, Hubble has
units of 1 over length--

01:04:53.670 --> 01:04:56.215
excuse me, 1 over time,
and with the factor

01:04:56.215 --> 01:04:57.590
of the speed of
light that is a 1

01:04:57.590 --> 01:05:01.130
over length, so one over
the Hubble parameter now

01:05:01.130 --> 01:05:03.380
is essentially a kind of
fiducial overall distance

01:05:03.380 --> 01:05:04.800
scale.

01:05:04.800 --> 01:05:13.040
And then our solution breaks
up into three branches,

01:05:13.040 --> 01:05:18.140
depending upon whether k
equals minus 1, 0, or 1.

01:05:20.710 --> 01:05:26.460
So you get one term where it
involves minus square root

01:05:26.460 --> 01:05:32.025
the absolute value of the
curvature parameter times sine.

01:05:35.980 --> 01:05:38.620
That same absolute value of
the curvature parameters square

01:05:38.620 --> 01:05:39.120
root.

01:05:55.780 --> 01:05:59.220
So here's your k
equals plus 1 branch.

01:05:59.220 --> 01:06:02.800
For your k equals 0
branch, basically what

01:06:02.800 --> 01:06:07.300
you'll find when you
plug-in your s of k

01:06:07.300 --> 01:06:09.400
is that r0 cancels out.

01:06:12.460 --> 01:06:15.100
So that ends up
being a parameter

01:06:15.100 --> 01:06:17.920
you do not need to worry
about, and I suggest you just

01:06:17.920 --> 01:06:19.450
work through the
algebra and you'll

01:06:19.450 --> 01:06:28.450
find that for k equals 0,
it simply looks like this.

01:06:31.980 --> 01:06:36.659
And then finally, if you
are in an open universe--

01:06:46.450 --> 01:06:48.135
that is supposed
to be curvature--

01:07:11.430 --> 01:07:12.480
what we get is this.

01:07:22.003 --> 01:07:23.420
So this is a
distance measure that

01:07:23.420 --> 01:07:27.740
tells me how angular
diameter distance depends

01:07:27.740 --> 01:07:29.540
on observable parameters.

01:07:29.540 --> 01:07:31.520
Hubble is something
that we can measure.

01:07:31.520 --> 01:07:33.830
Redshift is something
we can measure.

01:07:33.830 --> 01:07:36.840
And it depends on
model parameters,

01:07:36.840 --> 01:07:40.317
the different densities
that go into e of z, and--

01:07:40.317 --> 01:07:41.900
which I have on the
board right here--

01:07:44.940 --> 01:07:47.000
the different densities
that go into e of z.

01:07:47.000 --> 01:07:49.880
My apologies, I left
out that h0 there--

01:07:49.880 --> 01:07:55.170
and your choice
of the curvature.

01:07:55.170 --> 01:07:59.660
When you analyze
these three distances

01:07:59.660 --> 01:08:00.765
here is what you find.

01:08:21.910 --> 01:08:25.770
You find that the
luminosity distance

01:08:25.770 --> 01:08:29.990
is related to the proper motion
distance by a factor of 1

01:08:29.990 --> 01:08:36.210
plus z, and that's related to
the angular diameter distance

01:08:36.210 --> 01:08:38.439
by a factor of 1 plus z squared.

01:08:38.439 --> 01:08:42.000
So when you read Carroll, you
will find that 1 plus z factor

01:08:42.000 --> 01:08:43.260
there--

01:08:43.260 --> 01:08:47.637
excuse me, 1 plus z to the minus
1 power turns into a 1 plus z--

01:08:47.637 --> 01:08:48.970
is the camera not looking at me?

01:08:48.970 --> 01:08:49.470
Hello?

01:08:49.470 --> 01:08:50.279
There we go.

01:08:50.279 --> 01:08:56.955
So that 1 over 1 plus z
turns into a 1 plus z.

01:08:56.955 --> 01:08:59.580
When you do it on the p set, you
do the proper motion distance,

01:08:59.580 --> 01:09:03.359
so it will just be no 1 plus z
factor in front of everything.

01:09:03.359 --> 01:09:07.290
So the name of the game
when one is doing cosmology

01:09:07.290 --> 01:09:11.910
as a physicist is
to find quantities

01:09:11.910 --> 01:09:14.729
that you can measure that
allow you to determine

01:09:14.729 --> 01:09:18.479
luminosity distances,
angular diameter distances,

01:09:18.479 --> 01:09:20.189
proper motion distances.

01:09:20.189 --> 01:09:23.220
Now it turns out that the
proper motion distance

01:09:23.220 --> 01:09:26.880
is not a very practical
one for basically

01:09:26.880 --> 01:09:29.310
any cosmologically
interesting source.

01:09:29.310 --> 01:09:33.270
They are simply so far
away that even for a source

01:09:33.270 --> 01:09:35.910
moving essentially at
the speed of light,

01:09:35.910 --> 01:09:37.710
the amount of
angular motion that

01:09:37.710 --> 01:09:42.819
can be seen over essentially a
human lifetime is negligible.

01:09:42.819 --> 01:09:46.000
So this turns into
something that--

