01:10:08.040 --> 01:10:10.090
there, but it's all good.

01:10:10.090 --> 01:10:12.390
All right, so let's go
back to this for a second.

01:10:12.390 --> 01:10:15.372
So the proper motion
distance is something

01:10:15.372 --> 01:10:16.830
that is not
particularly practical,

01:10:16.830 --> 01:10:19.330
because as I said, even if you
have an object that is moving

01:10:19.330 --> 01:10:24.450
close to the speed of
light this is not something

01:10:24.450 --> 01:10:26.790
that even over the course
of a human lifetime

01:10:26.790 --> 01:10:30.550
you are likely to see
significant angular motion.

01:10:30.550 --> 01:10:32.160
So this is generally not used.

01:10:32.160 --> 01:10:35.160
But luminosity distances and
angular diameter distances,

01:10:35.160 --> 01:10:38.340
that is, in fact,
extremely important,

01:10:38.340 --> 01:10:45.990
and a lot of cosmology is based
on looking for well understood

01:10:45.990 --> 01:10:49.440
objects where we can
calibrate the physical size

01:10:49.440 --> 01:10:51.330
and infer the angular
diameter distance,

01:10:51.330 --> 01:10:53.820
or we know the
intrinsic brightness

01:10:53.820 --> 01:10:56.700
and we can determine
the luminosity distance.

01:10:56.700 --> 01:10:59.670
So let me just give
a quick snapshot

01:10:59.670 --> 01:11:02.580
of where the measurements come
from in modern cosmology that

01:11:02.580 --> 01:11:04.650
are driving our
cosmological model.

01:11:17.470 --> 01:11:20.498
One of the most important is
the cosmic microwave background.

01:11:28.630 --> 01:11:32.130
So, vastly oversimplifying, when
we look at the cosmic microwave

01:11:32.130 --> 01:11:38.910
background after removing
things like the flow

01:11:38.910 --> 01:11:43.490
of our solar system with respect
to the rest frame of-- excuse

01:11:43.490 --> 01:11:45.000
me, the co-moving
reference frame

01:11:45.000 --> 01:11:46.710
of the cause of the
fluid that makes up

01:11:46.710 --> 01:11:51.240
our universe, the size
of hot and cold spots

01:11:51.240 --> 01:11:52.140
is a standard ruler.

01:12:07.200 --> 01:12:08.970
By looking at the
distribution of sizes

01:12:08.970 --> 01:12:11.040
that we see from
these things, we

01:12:11.040 --> 01:12:14.003
can determine the
angular diameter distance

01:12:14.003 --> 01:12:15.420
to the cosmic
microwave background

01:12:15.420 --> 01:12:17.130
with very high precision.

01:12:17.130 --> 01:12:20.310
This ends up being one of the
most important constraints

01:12:20.310 --> 01:12:23.070
on determining what the
curvature parameter actually

01:12:23.070 --> 01:12:24.450
is.

01:12:24.450 --> 01:12:27.300
And it is largely thanks to
the cosmic microwave background

01:12:27.300 --> 01:12:33.500
that current prejudice, I would
say, the current best wisdom--

01:12:33.500 --> 01:12:36.800
choose your descriptor
as you wish--

01:12:36.800 --> 01:12:39.080
is that k equals
0 and our universe

01:12:39.080 --> 01:12:40.340
is in fact spatially flat.

01:12:43.370 --> 01:12:48.453
Second one is what are
called type 1a supernova.

01:12:57.330 --> 01:13:03.150
These are essentially the
thermonuclear detonations

01:13:03.150 --> 01:13:04.140
of white dwarfs.

01:13:11.320 --> 01:13:13.070
Not even really
thermonuclear, it's just--

01:13:17.725 --> 01:13:19.600
my apologies, I'm
confusing a different event

01:13:19.600 --> 01:13:21.275
that involves white dwarfs.

01:13:21.275 --> 01:13:22.900
The type 1a's are
not the thermonuclear

01:13:22.900 --> 01:13:24.025
explosions of these things.

01:13:24.025 --> 01:13:26.900
This is actually the core
collapse of a white dwarf star.

01:13:26.900 --> 01:13:30.610
So this is what happens when
a white dwarf it creates

01:13:30.610 --> 01:13:33.220
or in some way
accumulates enough mass

01:13:33.220 --> 01:13:37.300
such that electron
degeneracy pressure is

01:13:37.300 --> 01:13:40.780
no longer sufficient to hold it
against gravitational collapse,

01:13:40.780 --> 01:13:45.790
and the whole thing basically
collapses into a neutron star.

01:13:45.790 --> 01:13:49.270
That happens at a defined
mass, the Chandrasekhar mass,

01:13:49.270 --> 01:13:52.180
named after one of my
scientific heroes, Subramanian

01:13:52.180 --> 01:13:54.910
Chandrasekhar.

01:13:54.910 --> 01:13:59.830
And because it has a defined
mass associated with it,

01:13:59.830 --> 01:14:01.600
every event basically
has the same amount

01:14:01.600 --> 01:14:03.040
of matter participating.

01:14:03.040 --> 01:14:04.810
This is a standard candle.

01:14:22.035 --> 01:14:23.660
So there's a couple
others that I'm not

01:14:23.660 --> 01:14:26.150
going to talk about in
too much detail here.

01:14:26.150 --> 01:14:28.500
While I'm erasing the board
I will just mention them.

01:14:28.500 --> 01:14:32.150
So by looking at things like
the clustering of galaxies

01:14:32.150 --> 01:14:38.510
we can measure the
distribution of mass

01:14:38.510 --> 01:14:41.360
in the universe that allows
us to determine the omega m

01:14:41.360 --> 01:14:42.560
parameter.

01:14:42.560 --> 01:14:44.120
That's one of the
bits of information

01:14:44.120 --> 01:14:47.000
that tells us that
much of the universe

01:14:47.000 --> 01:14:49.790
is made of matter that
apparently does not

01:14:49.790 --> 01:14:51.650
participate in standard
model processes

01:14:51.650 --> 01:14:52.890
as we know them today--

01:14:52.890 --> 01:14:55.430
the so-called dark
matter problem.

01:14:55.430 --> 01:14:58.490
We can look at chemical
abundances, which tells us

01:14:58.490 --> 01:15:01.340
about the behavior of
nuclear processes in the very

01:15:01.340 --> 01:15:02.800
early universe.

01:15:02.800 --> 01:15:04.550
And the last one which
I will mention here

01:15:04.550 --> 01:15:10.355
is we can look at
nearby standard candles.

01:15:16.760 --> 01:15:18.890
And nearby standard
candles allow

01:15:18.890 --> 01:15:22.350
us to probe the local
Hubble law and determine h0.

01:15:26.392 --> 01:15:27.600
"Probble," that's not a word.

01:15:30.410 --> 01:15:33.570
If you combine "probe" and
"Hubble" you get "probble."

01:15:40.150 --> 01:15:42.120
And when I say
nearby, that usually

01:15:42.120 --> 01:15:45.157
means events that are merely
a few tens of millions

01:15:45.157 --> 01:15:45.990
of light years away.

01:15:48.720 --> 01:15:53.343
It's worth noting that all
of these various techniques,

01:15:53.343 --> 01:15:55.760
all of these different things,
you can kind of even see it

01:15:55.760 --> 01:15:58.093
when you think about the
mathematical form of everything

01:15:58.093 --> 01:16:00.530
that went into our
distance measures,

01:16:00.530 --> 01:16:02.970
they're all highly
entangled with each other.

01:16:02.970 --> 01:16:05.660
And so to do this kind
of thing properly,

01:16:05.660 --> 01:16:08.000
you need to take just
a crap load of data,

01:16:08.000 --> 01:16:10.580
combine all of your
data sets, and do

01:16:10.580 --> 01:16:14.240
a joint analysis of
everything, looking at the way

01:16:14.240 --> 01:16:17.480
varying the parameters and
all the different models

01:16:17.480 --> 01:16:19.913
affects the outcome
of your observables.

01:16:24.080 --> 01:16:26.510
You also have to carefully
take into account the fact

01:16:26.510 --> 01:16:29.900
that when you measure something,
you measure it with errors.

01:16:29.900 --> 01:16:31.920
And so many of these
things are not known.

01:16:31.920 --> 01:16:33.920
Turns out you can usually
measure redshift quite

01:16:33.920 --> 01:16:36.203
precisely, but these
distances always

01:16:36.203 --> 01:16:38.120
come with some error bar
associated with them.

01:16:38.120 --> 01:16:40.220
And so that means that
the distance you associate

01:16:40.220 --> 01:16:42.170
with a particular
redshift, which

01:16:42.170 --> 01:16:45.048
is equivalent to associating
a time with a redshift,

01:16:45.048 --> 01:16:46.340
there's some error bar on that.

01:16:46.340 --> 01:16:49.610
And that can lead to
significant skew in what you

01:16:49.610 --> 01:16:50.570
determine from things.

01:16:56.090 --> 01:16:58.922
There's a lot more we could
say, but time is finite

01:16:58.922 --> 01:17:00.380
and we need to
change topic, so I'm

01:17:00.380 --> 01:17:05.840
going to conclude this lecture
by talking about two mysteries

01:17:05.840 --> 01:17:08.270
in the cosmological
model that have been

01:17:08.270 --> 01:17:11.780
the focus of a lot
of research attention

01:17:11.780 --> 01:17:15.220
over the past several decades.

01:17:15.220 --> 01:17:15.970
Two mysteries.

01:17:15.970 --> 01:17:20.870
One, why is it that
our universe appears

01:17:20.870 --> 01:17:23.950
to be flat, spatially flat?

01:17:45.220 --> 01:17:47.040
So to frame why this
is a bit of a mystery,

01:17:47.040 --> 01:17:49.510
you did just sort
of go, eh, come on.

01:17:49.510 --> 01:17:52.450
You've got three choices for
the parameter, you got 0.

01:17:58.650 --> 01:18:01.170
Let's begin by thinking about
the first Friedmann equation.

01:18:16.350 --> 01:18:22.790
I can write this
like so, or I can

01:18:22.790 --> 01:18:28.070
use this form, where I say
omega plus omega curvature--

01:18:28.070 --> 01:18:31.220
I'm going to call
that omega c for now--

01:18:31.220 --> 01:18:32.060
that equals 1.

01:18:37.040 --> 01:18:41.750
The expectation had long
been that our universe would

01:18:41.750 --> 01:18:45.230
basically be dominated by
various species of matter

01:18:45.230 --> 01:18:49.020
and radiation for
much of its history,

01:18:49.020 --> 01:18:50.785
especially in the
early universe.

01:19:23.240 --> 01:19:26.430
If it was radiation
dominated, you'd

01:19:26.430 --> 01:19:31.800
expect the density to
go as a to the minus 4.

01:19:35.030 --> 01:19:36.530
If it's matter
dominated, you expect

01:19:36.530 --> 01:19:37.880
it to go as a to the minus 3.

01:19:44.620 --> 01:19:48.280
Now, your curvature density
goes as a to the minus 2.

01:20:22.680 --> 01:20:24.610
And so what this
means is that if you

01:20:24.610 --> 01:20:33.980
look at the ratio of
omega curvature to omega,

01:20:33.980 --> 01:20:41.360
this will be proportional
to a, for matter,

01:20:41.360 --> 01:20:50.180
a squared for radiation.

01:20:50.180 --> 01:20:56.820
If your universe--
in some sense,

01:20:56.820 --> 01:21:00.768
looking at these parameter
k of the minus 1, 0, 1,

01:21:00.768 --> 01:21:02.060
that's a little bit misleading.

01:21:02.060 --> 01:21:03.330
It's probably a little
bit more useful to think

01:21:03.330 --> 01:21:05.430
about things in terms
of the kappa parameter.

01:21:05.430 --> 01:21:08.820
And when you look at
that, your flat universe

01:21:08.820 --> 01:21:13.350
is a set of measure 0 in the
set of all possible curvature

01:21:13.350 --> 01:21:15.330
parameters that you could have.

01:21:15.330 --> 01:21:19.050
And physicists tend
to get suspicious

01:21:19.050 --> 01:21:24.060
when something that
could take on any range

01:21:24.060 --> 01:21:26.340
of possible random values
between minus infinity

01:21:26.340 --> 01:21:29.160
and infinity picks out zero.

01:21:29.160 --> 01:21:30.660
That tends to tell
us that there may

01:21:30.660 --> 01:21:32.970
be some principle at play
that actually derives things

01:21:32.970 --> 01:21:33.630
to being 0.

01:21:36.210 --> 01:21:37.950
Looking at it this
way, imagine you

01:21:37.950 --> 01:21:40.830
have a universe
that at early times

01:21:40.830 --> 01:21:47.160
is very close to being
flat, but not quite.

01:21:51.360 --> 01:22:07.200
Any slight deviation
from flatness

01:22:07.200 --> 01:22:10.620
grows as the universe expands.

01:22:16.990 --> 01:22:19.560
That's mystery one.

01:22:19.560 --> 01:22:30.090
Mystery two, why is the
cosmic microwave background

01:22:30.090 --> 01:22:32.420
so homogeneous?

01:22:35.330 --> 01:22:38.640
So when we look at the
cosmic microwave background,

01:22:38.640 --> 01:22:44.120
we see that it has
the same properties.

01:22:44.120 --> 01:22:45.650
The light has the
same brightness,

01:22:45.650 --> 01:22:47.780
it has the same temperature
associated with it,

01:22:47.780 --> 01:22:50.217
to within in a part in 100,000.

01:22:50.217 --> 01:22:51.800
Now the standard
model of our universe

01:22:51.800 --> 01:22:54.740
tells us that at
very early times

01:22:54.740 --> 01:22:57.020
the universe was essentially
a dense hot plasma.

01:23:18.990 --> 01:23:27.080
This thing cooled as
the universe expanded,

01:23:27.080 --> 01:23:31.070
much the same way that
if you have a bag of gas,

01:23:31.070 --> 01:23:33.650
you squeeze it very
rapidly, it will get hot,

01:23:33.650 --> 01:23:37.520
you stretch it very
rapidly, it will cool.

01:23:42.440 --> 01:23:44.792
There's a few more details
of this in my notes,

01:23:44.792 --> 01:23:46.750
but when we look at this
one the things that we

01:23:46.750 --> 01:23:53.530
see is that in a universe that
is only driven by matter or by

01:23:53.530 --> 01:23:54.330
radiation--

01:24:01.860 --> 01:24:04.670
so the matter dominated and
radiation dominated picture--

01:24:16.510 --> 01:24:31.260
it shows us that points on
opposite sides of the sky

01:24:31.260 --> 01:24:34.320
were actually out of causal
contact with each other

01:24:34.320 --> 01:24:36.195
in the earliest moments
of the universe.

01:24:58.980 --> 01:25:01.800
In other words, I
look at the sky,

01:25:01.800 --> 01:25:07.650
and the patch of sky over
here was out of causal contact

01:25:07.650 --> 01:25:10.530
with the patch of sky
over here in the earliest

01:25:10.530 --> 01:25:12.960
days of the universe.

01:25:12.960 --> 01:25:14.900
And yet they had the
same temperature,

01:25:14.900 --> 01:25:19.490
which suggests that they
were in thermal equilibrium.

01:25:19.490 --> 01:25:23.930
How can two disparate,
unconnected patch of the sky

01:25:23.930 --> 01:25:26.510
have the same temperature
if they cannot exchange

01:25:26.510 --> 01:25:27.620
information?

01:25:30.093 --> 01:25:31.760
You could imagine it
being a coincidence

01:25:31.760 --> 01:25:33.968
if one little bit of the
sky has the same temperature

01:25:33.968 --> 01:25:37.350
as a bit of another
piece, but in fact,

01:25:37.350 --> 01:25:39.950
when you do this calculation,
you find huge patch of the sky

01:25:39.950 --> 01:25:42.690
could not communicate
with any other.

01:25:42.690 --> 01:25:49.550
And so how then is it that the
entire sky that we can observe

01:25:49.550 --> 01:25:52.520
has the same temperature
at the earliest

01:25:52.520 --> 01:25:56.020
times within a part in 100,000.

01:25:56.020 --> 01:25:58.580
You guys will explore this on--

01:25:58.580 --> 01:26:01.930
I believe it's
problem set eight.

01:26:01.930 --> 01:26:21.490
The solution to both of these
problems that has been proposed

01:26:21.490 --> 01:26:23.205
is cosmic inflation.

01:26:30.490 --> 01:26:34.250
So what you do is imagine
that at some earlier

01:26:34.250 --> 01:26:38.420
moment in the
universe, our universe

01:26:38.420 --> 01:26:41.423
was filled with
some strange field,

01:26:41.423 --> 01:26:43.340
and I'll describe the
properties of that field

01:26:43.340 --> 01:26:46.370
in just a moment, such
that it acted like it

01:26:46.370 --> 01:26:47.750
had a cosmological constant.

01:27:15.900 --> 01:27:18.990
In such an epic, the scale
factor of the universe

01:27:18.990 --> 01:27:24.382
goes as exponentially with
the square root of the size

01:27:24.382 --> 01:27:25.590
of the cosmological constant.

01:27:30.140 --> 01:27:33.740
What you find when you look at
this is that this-- it still,

01:27:33.740 --> 01:27:36.410
of course, goes as
a to the minus 2--

01:27:36.410 --> 01:27:37.520
but a to the minus--

01:27:37.520 --> 01:27:38.760
well, sorry.

01:27:38.760 --> 01:27:40.040
Let me back up for a second.

01:27:40.040 --> 01:27:43.370
So my scale factor in
this case you'll find

01:27:43.370 --> 01:27:48.360
goes are a to the
minus 2, and that's

01:27:48.360 --> 01:27:51.030
because the density associated
with the cosmological constant

01:27:51.030 --> 01:27:51.900
remains constant.

01:28:01.860 --> 01:28:03.830
So even if you start
in the early universe

01:28:03.830 --> 01:28:06.150
with some random value
for the curvature,

01:28:06.150 --> 01:28:10.070
if you are in this epic
of exponential inflation,

01:28:10.070 --> 01:28:12.530
just for-- you know, you have
to worry about timescales

01:28:12.530 --> 01:28:14.330
a little bit, but if
you do it long enough

01:28:14.330 --> 01:28:17.630
you can drive this
very, very close to 0.

01:28:17.630 --> 01:28:20.960
So much so that when
you then move forward,

01:28:20.960 --> 01:28:25.250
let's say you come out of this
period of cosmic inflation

01:28:25.250 --> 01:28:28.160
and you enter a universe that
is radiation dominated or matter

01:28:28.160 --> 01:28:31.160
dominated, it will
then begin to grow,

01:28:31.160 --> 01:28:34.800
but if you drive it sufficiently
close to 0 it doesn't matter.

01:28:34.800 --> 01:28:39.170
You're never going to catch up
with what inflation did to you.

01:28:39.170 --> 01:28:42.410
On the P set you will
also show that if you

01:28:42.410 --> 01:28:51.140
have a period of
inflation like this, then

01:28:51.140 --> 01:28:53.630
that also cures the problem
of piece of the sky being

01:28:53.630 --> 01:28:55.170
out of causal contact.

01:28:55.170 --> 01:28:56.870
So when you do
that, what you find

01:28:56.870 --> 01:29:03.470
is that essentially everything
is in causal contact early on.

01:29:03.470 --> 01:29:05.510
It may sort of come
out of causal contact

01:29:05.510 --> 01:29:09.480
after inflation has ended,
more on that in just a moment,

01:29:09.480 --> 01:29:11.660
and then things sort of
change as the universe

01:29:11.660 --> 01:29:12.500
continues to evolve.

